[30;1m50 | [0m[35m    A diagonal is an integer defined as :math:`D = j - i`, where *i* and[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m    *j* are sequence positions in the first and second sequence,[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m    respectively.[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35m    This means that two symbols at position *i* and *j* can only be[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35m    aligned to each other, if :math:`D_L \leq j - i \leq D_U`.[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35m    With increasing width of the diagonal band, the probability to find[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m    the optimal alignment, but also the computation time increases.[0m

[30;1m115 | [0m[35m    the banded alignment heuristic and the optimal alignment[0m
[30;1m116 | [0m[35m    algorithms :footcite:`Needleman1970, Smith1981`.[0m
[30;1m117 | [0m[35m    Those classical algorithms require :math:`O(m \cdot n)`[0m
[30;1m118 | [0m[35m    memory space and computation time for aligning two sequences with[0m
[30;1m119 | [0m[35m    lengths :math:`m` and :math:`n`, respectively.[0m
[30;1m120 | [0m[35m    The banded alignment algorithm reduces both requirements to[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35m    :math:`O(\min(m,n) \cdot (D_U - D_L))`.[0m
